title: Shift summary: Monday swing
text: SUMMARY: PAMM recovery followed by accelerator physics. BTS BPMs 4-9 were switched to SPARK modules. INJECTOR: The booster was unlocked and systems were all up by around 5pm. Autofill was in TUNE as needed for AP injections, with up to 300mV Q. The linac timing vernier needed a large adjustment, and the SPEAR Hettel knob was also adjusted to match. The BTS was standardized to the most recent config (21-27), but fill rate and efficiency were poor until several trajectory corrections were done. A new BTS config (22-01) was then saved and loaded. Another BTS config (22-02) was saved/loaded after the SPARK BPM program. Previous configs should still work OK, as the readback differences between the SPARK and Bergoz BPMs appear to be quite negligible. SPEAR: The ring hazards were unlocked around 4:30pm, but many MCORs were red and some MCOR bulk supplies would not turn on. This was fallout from one of the PAMM tasks (some MCOR control elements were moved to a UPS). The system manager resolved the issue remotely, and SPEAR was filled to 500mA by about 5:30pm. The BTS BPM program successfully replaced 4 of the Bergoz BPMs with SPARK units. BPMs 8 and 9 had already been switched to Spark modules last year, so only BPMs 1, 2, and 3 remain on Bergoz modules. A BTS config was saved after the switch, trajectory correction was done to make sure it still works OK, and 5-minute autofills were done for about half an hour to verify normal operation. The 6nm TRIBS program is still in progress at the end of the shift. MISC: The PR-2 camera had to be rebooted twice this shift.

title: * Re: We did not get a PLC Heartbeat Alarm, despite the FEE PPS PLC reporting absent heartbeat
text: To understand why the system responded the way it did, lets take a look at the signal path for a typical PPS PV: Data goes from a physical device (like a door microswitch), into a bit in the safety PLC. Then, the bit in the safety PLC is read by the Access Control PLC, and stored there. Then, a PPS IOC reads the bit from the Access Control PLC, and turns it into an EPICS PV. The heartbeat in this screenshot is the PLC-to-IOC heartbeat - it is monitoring the communication link between SIOC:FEEH:PP01 and the PLC. If the IOC stops communicating with the PLC, this heartbeat goes "ABSENT", the IOC to PLC Communication PV goes to "FAULT", and the heartbeat error count starts counting up. Because these PVs originate in the SIOC (not the PLC), they go red instead of purple. If the link between the IOC and PLC is broken, all the PVs that display bits from the PLC (door microswitches, E/O button statuses, etc) will freeze, but will turn purple to indicate that the values are invalid, and cannot be trusted. The "PLC Heartbeat" alarm (channel 17) is not looking at the PLC-to-IOC heartbeat. It is looking at the Access Control PLC to Safety PLC heartbeat (which I will call PLC-to-PLC for brevity). The PLC-to-PLC heartbeat is monitoring the communication link between the Access Control PLC and the Safety PLC. If *that* link is broken, the Access Control PLC is stuck with old, frozen data from the safety PLC. So the EPICS PVs freeze too, but in this case they don't turn purple. That's why we have the alarm, because there's no indicator in EPICS that the data is frozen in this case. In summary: the network communication disruption last night was between the Access Control PLC and the IOC. This disruption does not generate a heartbeat alarm. Here's an extra observation: Unfortunately, while IOC-to-PLC communication is disrupted, it is impossible to know if the PLC-to-PLC communication is OK. The PLC-to-PLC heartbeat fault is implemented as a bit in the access control PLC, which is turned into a "Heartbeat Fault" PV by the IOC (which you can find at LCLSHome -> PPS/FEEH -> FEE Heart Beats). Then, the Alarms and Warnings system looks at all the Heartbeat Fault PVs from FEE, NEH, and Linac West IOCs, sums them up, and if any are faulted, it triggers the alarm. If an Access Control PLC stops talking to its IOC, its Heartbeat Fault PV freezes, making it impossible to trigger the alarm.
